title: For Sale:  80 Percent Arms AR-15 Universal Easy Jig
postcontent: BUY ONLINE --> 80 Percent Arms AR-15 Universal Easy JigA universal Easy Jig for AR-15 80% lower receivers. This design fits almost every AR-15 lower brand and makes machining your 80% lower easier, faster and safer. The Easy Jig has a built-in drill/end-mill depth gauge for the trigger and rear-shelf pockets. A quick verification of depth setting eliminates slippage issues that can ruin parts. It also eliminates constant measuring to determine depth while milling. The Easy Jig is designed to hold tolerances using a common hand-drill. A drill press is not required, the milling is done with a router. Pocket drilling requires 10 holes drilled once. A traditional jig requires 42 holes to be drilled once, precisely aligned and clamped, then re-drilled to a larger diameter. The trigger pocket can be cut in 6 to 11 passes versus 25 passes required with a drill press. Hand-drilling the trigger group/safety selector holes is faster to setup. The whole process can be completed in 1 hour instead of 3 hours with the old drill press method. The Easy Jig can be used to make dozens of lowers. All components are type III hard anodized for extra wear resistance. MADE IN THE U.S.A.NOTE: A router is NOT included.

title: For Sale:  Bushmaster Match XM15-E2S A2 (competition setup)
postcontent:
2001 birth date confirmed by Bushmaster
The rifle is 100% Bushmaster and original parts, except the mags
20” Heavy CHROME Barrel (also known as HBAR)
Chambered in 5.56, also suitable for .223 (not all ARs are suitable for 5.56)
Comes with (2) Colt30 round magazines and (1) Colt 15 round magazine - the only parts not original

A2 style upper

It is a match rifle, so it has a weighted barrel and removable weight in the stock that comes out of a flip-down door in the butt stock.

This one also has what is known as a “low shelf” receiver. Most civilian AR-15 models will have a “high shelf” meaning that the metal has not been carved out, like it normally would be on an M-16. A low shelf is desirable because it allows for addition of a “DIAS” or “drop in auto sear”, which allows the gun to operate in full auto mode. Civilians can legally buy DIAS units, but only those that were manufactured prior to 1986, and only those that are registered with the ATF, with the approval of your local sheriff.

title: For Sale:  FNH USA FNP-45 4.5", .45 ACP, 3 Magazines, Trijicon Night Sights, Used in Excellent Condition
postcontent: Although many pistols are offered with ambidextrous features, few include as many as the FNP-45. In addition to the ambidextrous safety selector/de-cocker, it also includes a fully ambidextrous magazine release and the far-less-common slide lock/slide release, providing left- and right-handed shooters all of the same controls. The take-down lever, however, remains exclusively on the left side of the pistol.The safety lever allows for cocked-and-locked carry with the Commander-style hammer back on a chambered round and the safety engaged. The safety disconnects the trigger bar when in the up position so the trigger moves freely but does not engage the hammer or fire the pistol. Pushing the safety selector down de-cocks the pistol, returning it from single-action mode to double-action. The de-cocker includes a mechanical block that prevents the hammer from making contact with the firing pin.Internally the FNP-45 also has a hammer-drop safety designed to prevent the pistol from firing if dropped, and the hammer has a half-cock notch. The gun will only fire if the trigger is fully depressed. Another valuable internal feature is the steel slide rails that are installed into the polymer frame. These can be factory replaced to extend the pistol’s service life.Further review can be found here: http://www.americanrifleman.org/articles/2012/1/27/fnh-usa-fnp-45-pistol/This FNP-45 is used and in Excellent condition. title: For Sale:  Colt Single Action Army Handgun
postcontent: The Colt Single Action Army revolver, alternately known as the Peacemaker, Model P, or Frontier, is the most popular handgun on the American Frontier and the definitive firearm of the Old West. The Single Action Army action is a refinement of the earlier Colt percussion revolvers and the Colt 1871 cartridge revolver. The cylinder is mounted on a central axis and operated by a hand with a double finger whose more extended action allowed the cylinder-ratchet to be cut in a larger circle, giving more torsional force to the cylinder. This 1894-manufacutured SAA is a late black powder model with a Colt authentication letter included. The bore has some minor pitting, but otherwise it's in NRA Good condition.
